{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631519"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17378"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17378"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75056"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10068"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60563"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7775"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23570"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher conducts a study examining the relationship between study hours per week (x) and final exam scores (y) in medical students. The statistical analysis produces a scatterplot with a regression line.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the interpretation of the coefficient of determination (R\u00b2) in this context?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The probability that the relationship occurred by chance","The percentage of students who passed the exam","The slope of the regression line between variables","The average change in exam score per hour studied","The proportion of variance in exam scores explained by study hours"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproportion of variance in exam scores explained by study hours\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the coefficient of determination (R\u00b2). This value ranges from 0 to 1 and indicates how much of the variability in the dependent variable (exam scores) can be explained by the independent variable (study hours).\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect interpretations are:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe probability that the relationship occurred by chance\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a p-value, not R\u00b2\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe slope of the regression line between variables\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the beta coefficient, which indicates the change in y per unit change in x\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe average change in exam score per hour studied\u003C/strong\u003E - This is another way of describing the slope, not R\u00b2\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe percentage of students who passed the exam\u003C/strong\u003E - This is an outcome measure unrelated to R\u00b2\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EFor example, an R\u00b2 of 0.64 would indicate that 64% of the variation in exam scores can be explained by differences in study hours, while the remaining 36% is due to other factors not included in the model.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["R\u00b2 - The coefficient of determination - is the proportion of variance in the dependent variable that is explained by the independent variable.","R\u00b2 values range from 0 to 1, where 1 indicates perfect prediction and 0 indicates no relationship.","R\u00b2 is calculated as the square of the Pearson correlation coefficient in simple linear regression."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60563"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17378"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60563"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T21:08:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T23:37:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10068"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75056"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t